{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Qubit gate decompositions of fermionic gates\n",
    "\n",
    "In this page, we discuss the gate decompositions of the fermionic gates included in ffsim.\n",
    "\n",
    "The following code cell constructs and draws an example circuit that uses some of the gates in ffsim. In the circuit drawing, the gates appear as opaque boxes. In the rest of this page, we'll see how these gates decompose into more basic gates."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 552.414x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 1,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from qiskit.circuit import QuantumCircuit, QuantumRegister\n",
    "\n",
    "import ffsim\n",
    "\n",
    "# Let's use 4 spatial orbitals with 2 alpha electrons and 2 beta electrons.\n",
    "norb = 4\n",
    "nelec = (2, 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initialize qubits\n",
    "qubits = QuantumRegister(2 * norb, name=\"q\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initialize random number generator\n",
    "rng = np.random.default_rng(1234)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generate some random data\n",
    "orbital_rotation = ffsim.random.random_unitary(norb, seed=rng)\n",
    "diag_coulomb_mat = ffsim.random.random_real_symmetric_matrix(norb, seed=rng)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create an example circuit\n",
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.PrepareHartreeFockJW(norb, nelec), qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.OrbitalRotationJW(norb, orbital_rotation), qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(\n",
    "    ffsim.qiskit.DiagCoulombEvolutionJW(norb, diag_coulomb_mat, time=1.0), qubits\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Draw the circuit\n",
    "circuit.draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Hartree-Fock and Slater determinant preparation\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's create a circuit with a Hartree-Fock state preparation gate. Then, let's decompose the circuit once and draw the output."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 201.247x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 2,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.PrepareHartreeFockJW(norb, nelec), qubits)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit.decompose().draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Hartree-Fock gate has decomposed into a Slater determinant gate. This makes sense, because the Hartree-Fock state is a special case of a Slater determinant. Let's go further and decompose the circuit using two repetitions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 142.72x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 3,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circuit.decompose(reps=2).draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, we see that the Hartree-Fock state preparation gate simply applies X gates to set the qubits corresponding to occupied orbitals to one.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Hartree-Fock state is defined as having the lowest numbered orbitals occupied. If we want to produce a different electronic configuration, we can use a more general Slater determinant preparation gate. Let's do this using a configuration obtained from the Hartree-Fock configuration by exciting one of the spin $\\alpha$ electrons to the next orbital."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 142.72x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "occupied_orbitals = ([0, 2], [0, 1])\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.PrepareSlaterDeterminantJW(norb, occupied_orbitals), qubits)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit.decompose().draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A general Slater determinant is obtained by applying an [orbital rotation](orbital-rotation.ipynb) to an electronic configuration. Let's generate a random orbital rotation and use it to initialize the gate."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 493.886x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 5,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "orbital_rotation = ffsim.random.random_unitary(norb, seed=rng)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(\n",
    "    ffsim.qiskit.PrepareSlaterDeterminantJW(\n",
    "        norb, occupied_orbitals, orbital_rotation=orbital_rotation\n",
    "    ),\n",
    "    qubits,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit.decompose().draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that the Slater determinant is prepared by applying X gates to prepare the Hartree-Fock configuration, and then applying a sequence of [XXPlusYYGates](https://docs.quantum.ibm.com/api/qiskit/qiskit.circuit.library.XXPlusYYGate#xxplusyygate) to effect the orbital rotation. Note that the initial X gates prepare the Hartree-Fock configuration even though we specified a different one in the gate initialization. This happens because the Slater determinant gate decomposition is optimized to minimize the number of XXPlusYYGates in the result. The decomposition is more efficient than that of a general orbital rotation. The pattern of XXPlusYYGates requires only linear qubit connectivity."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Orbital rotation\n",
    "\n",
    "A general orbital rotation decomposes into a sequence of XXPlusYYGates followed by a layer of [PhaseGates](https://docs.quantum.ibm.com/api/qiskit/qiskit.circuit.library.PhaseGate#phasegate). As with the Slater determinant preparation, the pattern of XXPlusYYGates requires only linear qubit connectivity."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 610.942x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "orbital_rotation = ffsim.random.random_unitary(norb, seed=rng)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.OrbitalRotationJW(norb, orbital_rotation), qubits)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit.decompose().draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Diagonal Coulomb evolution\n",
    "\n",
    "Time evolution by a diagonal Coulomb Hamiltonian decomposes into a layer of PhaseGates followed by a sequence of [CPhaseGates](https://docs.quantum.ibm.com/api/qiskit/qiskit.circuit.library.CPhaseGate#cphasegate)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1547.39x1018.38 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 7,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "diag_coulomb_mat = ffsim.random.random_real_symmetric_matrix(norb, seed=rng)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(\n",
    "    ffsim.qiskit.DiagCoulombEvolutionJW(norb, diag_coulomb_mat, time=1.0), qubits\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit.decompose().draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Unitary cluster Jastrow (UCJ) operator\n",
    "\n",
    "A UCJ operator decomposes into a sequence of diagonal Coulomb evolutions sandwiched by orbital rotations. The number of diagonal Coulomb evolutions is equal to the number of ansatz repetitions (in this example, two)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 903.581x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 8,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "n_reps = 2\n",
    "t2 = ffsim.random.random_t2_amplitudes(norb, nocc=nelec[0], dtype=float)\n",
    "ucj_op = ffsim.UCJOperator.from_parameters(\n",
    "    ffsim.UCJOperator.from_t_amplitudes(t2, n_reps=n_reps).to_parameters(),\n",
    "    norb=norb,\n",
    "    n_reps=n_reps,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.UCJOperatorJW(ucj_op), qubits)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit.decompose().draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Merging orbital rotations\n",
    "\n",
    "The gate decomposition displayed above is not optimal because it contains adjacent orbital rotation gates, which can be merged. In [How to build and transpile Qiskit quantum circuits](../how-to-guides/qiskit-circuits.ipynb#Circuit-transpilation) we showed how to use ffsim's transpiler passes to optimize circuits constructed from fermionic gates. Here, we explain how this works in a bit more detail.\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider a circuit that prepares the Hartree-Fock state and then applies a UCJ operator to it:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 376.831x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.PrepareHartreeFockJW(norb, nelec), qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.UCJOperatorJW(ucj_op), qubits)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit.draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's decompose the circuit once:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1020.64x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 10,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circuit.decompose().draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are two places that this circuit can be optimized:\n",
    "\n",
    "- The first two gates can be merged into a single Slater determinant preparation gate.\n",
    "- The fourth and fifth gates can be merged into a single orbital rotation gate.\n",
    "\n",
    "The following code cell performs this optimization using a pass manager consisting of the [MergeOrbitalRotations](../api/ffsim.qiskit.rst#ffsim.qiskit.MergeOrbitalRotations) pass."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 786.525x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 11,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from qiskit.transpiler import PassManager\n",
    "\n",
    "pass_manager = PassManager([ffsim.qiskit.MergeOrbitalRotations()])\n",
    "transpiled = pass_manager.run(circuit.decompose())\n",
    "\n",
    "transpiled.draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that the MergeOrbitalRotations pass needs to be run on the decomposed circuit. Running it on the original circuit will have no effect because the orbital rotations are not exposed:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 376.831x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 12,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "transpiled = pass_manager.run(circuit)\n",
    "\n",
    "transpiled.draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This issue can addressed by adding a [Decompose](https://docs.quantum.ibm.com/api/qiskit/qiskit.transpiler.passes.Decompose#decompose) pass that decomposes Hartree-Fock and UCJ gates before the MergeOrbitalRotations pass:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 786.525x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 13,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from qiskit.transpiler.passes import Decompose\n",
    "\n",
    "pass_manager = PassManager(\n",
    "    [\n",
    "        Decompose([\"hartree_fock_jw\", \"ucj_jw\"]),\n",
    "        ffsim.qiskit.MergeOrbitalRotations(),\n",
    "    ]\n",
    ")\n",
    "transpiled = pass_manager.run(circuit)\n",
    "\n",
    "transpiled.draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The [pre_init_passes](../api/ffsim.qiskit.rst#ffsim.qiskit.pre_init_passes) function returns a generator that yields these transpiler passes. The function is so named because we recommend using these passes for the `pre_init` stage of Qiskit's transpiler pipeline. You can construct a pass manager using this function as follows:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "pre_init = PassManager(list(ffsim.qiskit.pre_init_passes()))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's do a full transpilation of the circuit with and without the `pre_init` passes, and then print the final gate counts."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Gate counts without pre_init passes:\n",
      "OrderedDict([('cp', 56), ('xx_plus_yy', 48), ('p', 32), ('x', 4)])\n",
      "\n",
      "Gate counts with pre_init passes:\n",
      "OrderedDict([('cp', 56), ('xx_plus_yy', 32), ('p', 24), ('x', 4)])\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from qiskit.providers.fake_provider import GenericBackendV2\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler.preset_passmanagers import generate_preset_pass_manager\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initialize quantum device backend\n",
    "backend = GenericBackendV2(2 * norb, basis_gates=[\"cp\", \"xx_plus_yy\", \"p\", \"x\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a pass manager for circuit transpilation\n",
    "pass_manager = generate_preset_pass_manager(optimization_level=3, backend=backend)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Transpile the circuit without pre_init passes\n",
    "transpiled = pass_manager.run(circuit)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Transpile the circuit with pre_init passes\n",
    "pass_manager.pre_init = pre_init\n",
    "transpiled_opt = pass_manager.run(circuit)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Gate counts without pre_init passes:\")\n",
    "print(transpiled.count_ops())\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(\"Gate counts with pre_init passes:\")\n",
    "print(transpiled_opt.count_ops())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The XXPlusYYGate count is significantly reduced when the `pre_init` passes are used.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Locality in the UCJ operator\n",
    "\n",
    "Recall that the UCJ operator decomposes into orbital rotations and diagonal Coulomb evolutions. As explained [previously](#Orbital-rotation), orbital rotations decompose into a pattern of XXPlusYYGates that can be implemented using only linear qubit connectivity. However, the diagonal Coulomb evolutions decompose into a pattern of controlled phase gates which in general require all-to-all connectivity, and their implementation on a limited connectivity qubit device would involve the insertion of swap gates. The following code cell decomposes the diagonal Coulomb evolution in a UCJ operator and draws the resulting circuit."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1547.39x1018.38 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 16,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "n_reps = 1\n",
    "\n",
    "ucj_op = ffsim.UCJOperator.from_parameters(\n",
    "    ffsim.UCJOperator.from_t_amplitudes(t2, n_reps=n_reps).to_parameters(),\n",
    "    norb=norb,\n",
    "    n_reps=n_reps,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.UCJOperatorJW(ucj_op), qubits)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit.decompose([\"ucj_jw\", \"diag_coulomb_jw\"], reps=2).draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {
    "779ec75b-28ff-47e5-b7c0-609fe7e8c53b.png": {
     "image/png": ""
    }
   },
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The [local UCJ](../how-to-guides/lucj.ipynb) ansatz is more amenable to qubit hardware with limited connectivity. It works by allowing only certain entries of the diagonal Coulomb matrix to be nonzero. The pattern of nonzero entries is motivated by the connectivity of the target hardware. For example, if the connectivity is that of a square lattice, we can map the spin $\\alpha$ orbitals and spin $\\beta$ orbitals onto adjacent lines:\n",
    "\n",
    "![square_lattice.png](attachment:779ec75b-28ff-47e5-b7c0-609fe7e8c53b.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "The available connections between orbitals with the same spin are referred to as the `alpha_alpha` connections, and those between orbitals of different spin are referred to as the `alpha_beta` connections. The following code cell initializes a local UCJ operator specifying these connections."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1137.69x491.633 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "alpha_alpha_indices = [(p, p + 1) for p in range(norb - 1)]\n",
    "alpha_beta_indices = [(p, p) for p in range(norb)]\n",
    "\n",
    "ucj_op = ffsim.UCJOperator.from_parameters(\n",
    "    ffsim.UCJOperator.from_t_amplitudes(t2, n_reps=n_reps).to_parameters(),\n",
    "    norb=norb,\n",
    "    n_reps=n_reps,\n",
    "    alpha_alpha_indices=alpha_alpha_indices,\n",
    "    alpha_beta_indices=alpha_beta_indices,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit = QuantumCircuit(qubits)\n",
    "circuit.append(ffsim.qiskit.UCJOperatorJW(ucj_op), qubits)\n",
    "\n",
    "circuit.decompose([\"ucj_jw\", \"diag_coulomb_jw\"], reps=2).draw(\"mpl\", scale=0.7)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, there are much fewer controlled-phase gates, and the gates that are retained act on neighboring qubits if the orbitals are mapped onto a square lattice as described above."
   ]
  }
 ],
